04180nam a22005295i 9780804764346DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047643467 a10.1515/97808047643462doi  a(DE-B1597)582331  a(OCoLC)1312727146  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHC430.C6.G56 2000eb 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a306.3/0951/431 aGillette, Maris Boyd, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Mecca and Beijing :bModernization and Consumption Among Urban Chinese Muslims /cMaris Boyd Gillette. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b20 illustrations, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tCHAPTER ONE Modernization and Consumption -- tCHAPTER TWO Housing, Education, and Race -- tCHAPTER THREE Mosques, Qur'anic Education, and Arabization -- tCHAPTER FOUR Traditional Food and Race -- tCHAPTER FIVE Factory Food, Modernization, and Race -- tCHAPTER SIX Alcohol and "Building a Civilized Society" -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Wedding Gowns and Modernization -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Consumption and Modernization -- tAppendix -- tCharacter List -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween Mecca and Beijing examines how a community of urban Chinese Muslims uses consumption to position its members more favorably within the Chinese government's official paradigm for development. Residents of the old Muslim district in the ancient Chinese capital of Xi'an belong to an official minority (the Hui nationality) that has been classified by the state as "backward" in comparison to China's majority (Han) population. Though these Hui urbanites, like the vast majority of Chinese citizens, accept the assumptions about social evolution upon which such labels are based, they actively reject the official characterization of themselves as less civilized and modern than the Han majority. By selectively consuming goods and adopting fashions they regard as modern and non-Chinese—which include commodities and styles from both the West and the Muslim world—these Chinese Muslims seek to demonstrate that they are capable of modernizing without the guidance or assistance of the state. In so doing, they challenge one of the fundamental roles the Chinese Communist government has claimed for itself, that of guide and purveyor of modernity. Through a detailed study of the daily life—eating habits, dress styles, housing, marriage and death rituals, religious practices, education, family organization—of the Hui inhabitants of Xi'an, the author explores the effects of a state-sponsored ideology of progress on an urban Chinese Muslim neighborhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aReligion -- Asian. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080473694740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476434640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764346423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764346/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles